==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno|en}} {{term|revestier|lang=fro}}, {{term|revestre}} et al., {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|revestir|lang=frm}}, and their source, {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|revestire}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|re-|lang=la}} + {{term|vestire|vestīre|to clothe}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ɹiːˈvɛst/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|obsolete}} To [[dress]] (a priest or other religious figure) in ritual garments, especially to celebrate Mass or another service.
# To [[reclothe]]; to dress again.
#* '''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', II.i:
#*: Her nathelesse / Th'enchaunter finding fit for his intents, / Did thus '''reuest''', and deckt with due habiliments.
# To return (property) to a former owner; to [[reinstate]]
# To invest again with possession or office.
#: ''to '''revest''' a magistrate with authority''

